@Veronica I can appreciate your point about the label of "not as bad" being a stigmatising way to label a narcissist. I agree that nobody is born bad, as I said it is often a result of maltreatment during childhood which would cause narcissism and other personality disorders but this is in combination with genetics. Maybe "bad" is the wrong language and I agree that i wouldn't use this terminology in my professional practice working with patients with NPD and this is rather personal. But a lack of empathy isn't exactly a positive trait to have and leads to treating others extremely poorly. Also I disagree that narcissism is a mental illness. I see it as more of a mental health condition which needs to be managed as it is not curable or treatable with medication. From what I am experiencing and what I am hearing about narcissists they often appear to not want to get help or change because they do not see an issue in their actions and genuinely think that they are the victim in many situations despite being aware that they have caused other people harm. I feel that saying "The choice is up to you" is stigmatising in a way though because actually it's not our responsibility? It's theirs. As I say, they have their own vulnerabilities but they are still very much aware of what they are doing and how they are behaving. I agree we should encourage narcissists to get the help that they need and to go to therapy but everybody, especially those of us who have been victims to narcissists must not place this responsibility on ourselves.
